Installing Matplotlib

Importing and Installing Matplotlib

matplotlib can be installed using the pip command as given below

pip install matplotlib

Note : Its always a best practice to install python libraries only for a particular user like pip install matplotlib --user, which installs the libraries to your local directory such as /home/user/ instead of /usr/local/lib/python which requires root access.

Further, It is advised to use the virtual enviroinment available within python to install any packages so that your libraries will not be interfered by any other installed libraries outside the virtual enviroinment. More details about the virtual enviroinment can be found here

https://www.freecodecamp.org/news/how-to-setup-virtual-environments-in-python/

Basic Plotting with matplotlib

Matplotlib can be imported into our code by using

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

  • the pyplot class provides us with high level functions which can directly be used to create instant plots without much effort

  • For Eg, A basic line plot can be called using the plot function within the pyplot utility

Points to Note :

  1. matplotlib does not require xaxis values to be provided for plotting, however if x axis values are specified, then both arrays should have same length
  2. The arrays can be of strings or numbers, depending on the plot, matplotlib will plot the values accordingly

Note : Try plotting a list of strings using line plot and observe what happens

plt functions ( for overall plot )

function Description
title() Adds title to the given plot
legend() Adds legend to the given plot based on labels provided.
text() Adds a text box in the plot area
xlabel() Adds x label to the given plot
grid() Adds grid lines to the given plots
show() Displays the plot in the current window ( useful in terminal based enviroinments )

Title

  • The title method provides functionality to add title to the existing plot object

  • You can provide additional parameters to the title using the font dict params.

dictVal = {'fontsize': 30,
 'fontweight': 'bold',
 'color': 'b',
 'verticalalignment': 'baseline',
 'horizontalalignment': 'center'}

plt.title("Sample Title, dictVal)

Additional Details

Legend

  • The title method provides functionality to add legends to the existing plots. The legend method has multiple parameters like

    • loc -- Decides where the legend have to be placed
    • bbox_to_anchor -- usefull when we need to place the legend outside the plots

Additional Details

Marker

Adds marker to the points based on the symbols as mentioned below

color

Adjusts the color of the given line plot

Line Style

More details about the plot parameters can be found in https://matplotlib.org/stable/api/_as_gen/matplotlib.pyplot.plot.html#matplotlib.pyplot.plot

Marker

  • Adds marker to the points based on the interval provided with this value

Label

  • Adds label to the given line , which will be used for plotting legends ( without labels for line, the legends cannot be added to the existing plots )

linewidth

  • Adjusts the line width of the plotted line

Now lets start adding features to the existing plot..!

Axis limits and Axis labels

This is one of the most freqquent problem that we night encounter into while generating plots.

  • xticks,yticks
  • xticklabels, yticklabels
  • xlim,ylim

xlim

========

controlls the limit on both x and y axis plot. this can be used to highlight only specific portions of the graph

xticks and xticklabels

==========================

xticks are the parameters which deceides which values to be displayed as ticks ( small vertical lines on the axis of plots,which forms the basis of grid() method ).

Note :

  • Matplotlib automatically adjusts the xticks values to an optimal value, based on the size of the plot and the number of x parameters
  • xticklabels labels defines the values that willp be displayed on the plots at the given values of xticks

-All text related parameters such as fontsize, rotation, font weight can be controlled while providing the xticklables

  • The size of both xticks and xticklabels should be the same
  • The value of xticklabel will override the actual value of xticks(x array value) while plotting

For Eg :

plt.xtick([1,2,3],["Monday","Tuesday","Wednesday"])

In [ ]:

Short Format Notation

matplotlib proivdes a short format notation for easily providing the line plot parameters. They are defined as follows

fmt = '[marker][line][color]'

'b'    # blue markers with default shape
'or'   # red circles
'-g'   # green solid line
'--'   # dashed line with default color
'^k:'  # black triangle_up markers connected by a dotted line
In [ ]:
Temperaturebangalore = [36,32,30,25,28,32,34,31,30,33]
TemperatureDelhi =     [40,39,31,35,39,37,36,35,34,38]
plt.figure(figsize=(6,4),dpi=100)
plt.plot(Temperaturebangalore,'^k:',label="Bengaluru")
plt.plot(TemperatureDelhi,'ob-',label="Delhi")
plt.legend()
plt.title("Temperature Bengaluru vs Delhi")
plt.show()

Latex Notations in Matplotlib

To use latex expressions like $f(x) = y^2$ or $10e^{-5}$ within the plots, we need to first activate the rcParams for matplotlib related to text.usetex

plt.rcParams['text.usetex'] = True

After this, we can enclose all the text with the r string ( Similar to what we do with fstrings in python )

for Eg

x = np.linspace(0.0, 1.0, 100)
y = [k*k for k in x]
plt.plot(x,y)
plt.xlabel(r'x')
plt.ylabel(r'$f(x) = y^{2}$')
plt.title(r'Sample Function with \TeX\ ')

Note : By default these wont work in all the systems, we need to have latex installed in our systems for these latex expressions and latex fonts to be rendered properly. They can be installed using

!sudo apt install cm-super dvipng texlive-latex-extra texlive-latex-recommended

More Details about this can be found here Matplotlib-Latex

Excersise 2¶

Clean up the histogram such that only top 5 man of the match candidates are shown and they are in sorted order. Do not use pandas library functions

Expected output

In [20]:
#@title Solution for Excersise 2

## dict (hashmap) approach Finishes in O(N), a count and loop method may take O(N^2) on worst case
count  = {}
for player in manofthematch:
  if player in count:
    count[player] += 1
  else:
    count[player] = 1

## now, we need to sort the dict based on keys
## [Ref link](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/613183/how-do-i-sort-a-dictionary-by-value)
newCount = {k: v for k, v in sorted(count.items(),reverse=True, key=lambda item: item[1])}

## Obtain First Five Values and plot
Player = list(newCount.keys())
mom = list(newCount.values())

plt.figure(figsize=(6,4),dpi=100)
# print(Player)
# print(mom)

plt.bar(Player[:5],mom[:5], color='r')

plt.show()

Plot a gaussian pdf with Mean at zero and standard deviation as 1 with the area under the gaussian curve. Shade each regions seperately based on their sigma values and use text to annotate them

The Output should look like below

In [21]:
#@title Solution for Gaussian

## get a normal distribution from numpy
## coded by : Divij Ghose
from scipy import stats

x_data = np.arange(-3, 3, 0.001)
y_data = stats.norm.pdf(x_data, 0, 1)
plt.figure(figsize=(6,4),dpi=100)
plt.plot(x_data,y_data,color='k')
colorlist = ['#F0F8FF','#98F5FF','#00688B','#104E8B']
xlabels = [r'$-3\sigma$',r'$-2\sigma$',r'$-1\sigma$',r'$\mu$',r'$1\sigma$',r'$2\sigma$',r'$3\sigma$']
for i in range(4):
    plt.fill_between(x_data[(i-1)*1000:i*1000],y_data[(i-1)*1000:i*1000],color=colorlist[i],alpha=i*0.25)    
    plt.fill_between(x_data[-i*1000:(i-1)*-1000-1],y_data[-i*1000:(i-1)*-1000-1],color=colorlist[i],alpha=i*0.25)
    plt.axvline(x=x_data[i*1000],color='w')
    plt.axvline(x=x_data[-(i*1000)],color='w')
    
plt.xticks(np.arange(-3,4,1),xlabels)
plt.text(0.1, 0.25, '34.1%',color='w')
plt.text(-0.75, 0.25, '34.1%',color='w')
plt.text(1.1, 0.01, '13.6%',color='w')
plt.text(-1.75,.01, '13.6%',color='w')
plt.text(2.2, 0.05, '2.1%',color='k')
plt.text(-2.8,.05, '2.1%',color='k')
plt.title("Gaussian Distribution with 0-Mean and 1-Std.Dev")

Difference between plt and ax,fig objects

The Major Challenge , that comes to people when they start learning matplotlib is understanding the difference between the plt object and the figure and axes object

What ever, we have learnt untill now, we have directly used the plt objects method to plot the necessary plots. Something like the one below

plt.figure(figsize=(6,4),dpi=100)
plt.plot(x, y, color='r')

However, if you ever refer to any tutorials otr help on stackoverflow, you will be comming across these syntaxes, which might look like

fig,ax = plt.subplots(2,2,figsize(6,4))  ## getting axes and Figure object
ax.plot(x, y)                            ## plot using axes object
fig.saveplt()                            ## Save Plot using the figure object

or

figure = plt.figure()                 ## Get a figure object
new_plot = figure.add_subplot(111)    ## Add an axes object onto the figure 
new_plot.plot(x, y)                   ## plot using the axes object

So, What is happening here?

It seems that the plt object is the wrapper that was made on top of existing matplotlib libraries to make sure the plotting syntaxes remain similar to the matlab's plotting syntax Reference

Lets try to understand what data these objects hold in general

Figure Object

This object acts like a canvas on which the plotting will be done. So the details such as size of the figure, number of subplots a figure has and saving/ exporting the figure will be contributed by this object.

The figure object can be initiated using plt.figure() or using the plt.subplots() or plt.subplot() object

Note : The Figure object will not be sufficient to add plots, we need axes object to make the actual plots within the canvas

In [ ]:
## obtain a figure object 
fig = plt.figure()

<Figure size 432x288 with 0 Axes>

Axes Object

The Axes object interacts with the underlying graphical libraries to generate the basic plotting objects such as a line2d, circle , etc. these artifacts are drawn based on the inputs given by the user and then placed on a canvas generated by the figure object.

The Axes object has menthods like plot(), bar() , scatter() etc and also the helper functions like set_title(), set_xlabel() , set_ylabel(), set_legend() etc

A axes object can be created and added to a figure object by either one of the below syntax

In [ ]:
## Create an axes and figure object directly
fig, axes = plt.subplots()

## OR 
fig = plt.figure()
ax = fig.add_subplot()

Plt Object

The plot object is the wrapper to both the axes and the figure object. When we create the plot object both axes object and the figure object are created and will be stored inside the internal datastructure of plt.

These objects can be extracted from the plt objects using the command plt.gcf() for figure and plt.gca() for axes

Hint

Most of the (not all) methods that are available with plt such as title , xlabel , ylabel will be available for axes as set_title, set_xlabel,set_ylabel

Creating subplots

We can create subplots by using the subplots() function. This function will return a grid of axes object which we can use to plot the subplots.

In [ ]:
#### FOUR DIFFERENT SUBPLOTS
import numpy as np
fig, ax = plt.subplots(2,2,figsize=(11,8))

Tight Layout¶

This function call ensures that all the elements within the figure are properly spaced and there is no overlap between each subplot and ensures every object resides within the main canvas

The tight_layout() object also accepts attributes such as pad, w_pad and h_pad., which can further control the spacing between subplots.

Note : plt object has subplots_adjust() method which can add padding between subplots

import numpy as np

N = 3
ind = np.arange(N)  # the x locations for the groups

fig = plt.figure()
ax = fig.add_subplot(111)

yvals = [4, 9, 2]
rects1 = ax.bar(ind-(width), yvals, width, color='r')
zvals = [1,2,3]
rects2 = ax.bar(ind, zvals, width, color='g')
kvals = [11,12,13]
rects3 = ax.bar(ind+width, kvals, width, color='b')

ax.set_ylabel('Scores')
ax.set_xticks(ind+width)
ax.set_xticklabels( ('2011-Jan-4', '2011-Jan-5', '2011-Jan-6') )
ax.legend( (rects1[0], rects2[0], rects3[0]), ('y', 'z', 'k') )

def autolabel(rects):
    for rect in rects:
        h = rect.get_height()
        ax.text(rect.get_x()+rect.get_width()/2., 1.05*h, '%d'%int(h),
                ha='center', va='bottom')

autolabel(rects1)
autolabel(rects2)
autolabel(rects3)

plt.show()

Animations using Matplotlib¶

The Animation classes in matplotlib can be accomplished using these classes

  • Artistic Animation -- Uses the Artist objects to create the animation
  • Function Animation -- uses function, which will be called repeatitively to generate animations

Matplotlib Animation

Method - 1 : Render Each Frame Seperately¶

In this, we will use the pause() function within matplotlib to generate a plot, which will make it appear like an animation

In [39]:
y = ecg[300:4000:10]
t = time[300:4000:10]
 
## generate Plot Object 
fig,ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(6,4),tight_layout=True,dpi=100 )
 
for frame in range(len(y)):
    ax.clear()  ## Clear the Object
    ax.set_xlabel("Time(s)")
    ax.set_ylabel("ECG in mV")
    ax.grid()
    ax.plot(t[:frame],y[:frame],'ok-',markevery=[-1])
    ax.set_ylim([-1,1.5])
    fig.canvas.draw()
    plt.pause(0.00001)
    pass;

Method - 2 : Update the Line Elements(Artists Object)¶

In this, Rather than redrawing the entire plot, we can just modify the data which is stored in the line object to get the updated plots.

In [40]:
y = ecg[300:4000:10]
t = time[300:4000:10]
 
## generate Plot Object 
fig,ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(6,4),tight_layout=True,dpi=100 )

ln, = ax.plot([],[],'ok-',markevery=[-1]) ### Obtain the Line Object
ax.set_xlabel("Time(s)")
ax.set_ylabel("ECG in mV")

for frame in range(len(y)):
   

    ln.set_data(t[:frame],y[:frame])
    ax.grid()
    ax.plot(t[:frame],y[:frame],'ok-',markevery=[-1])   ## rather than clearing the canvas, just update the line object alone. 
    # ax.set_ylim([-1,1.5])
    ax.relim()
    fig.canvas.draw()
    plt.pause(0.00001)
    pass;

Check how these methods affect the frame rates rendered by these plots in this video

3. Using FuncAnimation and blit¶

This is matplotlib's inbuilt funcitonality to animate the plots by calling this functions again and again

  • init() -- Function initialises the plot
  • update() -- Function updates the artists objects to update the plot

blit is an intelligent way to update the graphics without much effort. Additional details about blit can be refered from this video

In [38]:
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
# from matplotlib import mp

y = ecg[300:10000:10]
t = time[300:10000:10]


fig, ax = plt.subplots()
xdata, ydata = [], []
ln, = ax.plot([], [], 'ok-')


## Intialises the plot
def init():
    ln, = ax.plot([],[],'ok-',markevery=[-1]) ### Obtain the Line Object
    ax.set_xlabel("Time(s)")
    ax.set_ylabel("ECG in mV")
    ax.set_ylim([-1,1.5])
    return ln,

## Updates the plot at each frame
def update(data):
    xdata.append(data[1])
    ydata.append(data[0])
    ln.set_data(xdata, ydata)
    ax.relim()
    return ln,

ani = FuncAnimation(fig, update, frames=list(zip(y,t)),
                    init_func=init, interval = 10, blit=True)
plt.show()
